SUMMARY:Jenner Headlands
DESCRIPTION:Go Wild Hikers\nA good day to look for wildflowers. Jenner Hea
 dlands is a spectacular 5\,630-acre mosaic of redwood and Douglas fir fore
 sts\, oak woodland\, chaparral\, and coastal prairie overlooking the Pacif
 ic Ocean. Coastal prairie is rare and only found along the Pacific Coast o
 f California and southern Oregon. These areas support a rich assemblage of
  native plants and are one of the most diverse types of grasslands in Nort
 h America. Many rare and endangered species inhabit the property including
  the northern spotted owl\, peregrine falcon\, and red tree vole. Deer\, b
 obcat\, coyote\, mountain lion and steelhead trout are also found on the p
 roperty. A challenging hike best for individuals and dogs with at least a 
 moderate level of fitness.\n\n**Where We Meet/Important Directions**\nJenn
 er Headlands Preserve\nHwy 1 Jenner\, Ca\n**Get there Early! Carpool if yo
 u can - This is a very Popular Park!**\nGive yourself plenty of time to ar
 rive and use restroom. It often takes longer than you think.\n\n**Six thin
 gs to remember when hiking near cattle**\n1- Properly latch any gates you 
 pass through on trails.\n2- Always keep dogs on leash. Do not let pets cha
 se or harass livestock.\nCows cannot distinguish the difference between a 
 coyote and a dog.\n3- If cattle are blocking the trail\, approach them slo
 wly\, speak normally\, and allow them to move away. If they don’t move a
 way on their own\, provide a wide berth by walking around them off-trail\,
  if necessary.\n4- If you see a stray calf\, leave it alone\; the mother i
 s often feeding or watering nearby and will return. Do not get between a m
 other cow and young calves.\n5- Give space to any cow that shows signs of 
 aggression. This may mean giving them lots of space and walking off-trail 
 if necessary.\n6- If you encounter a cow that is acting in a threatening m
 anner\, or appears to be injured\, sick or dead\, please note the location
 \, the color of the animal\, the ear tag number\, and report it to the par
 k.\nhttps://parks.sonomacounty.ca.gov/Learn/Blog/Articles/Sharing-Sonoma-C
 ounty-trails-with-cows/\n\n**The Hike (Group Hike #339)**\nSea to Sky and 
 Raptor Ridge trails - A loop hike\nLength - +/-5 miles/8.1 kilometers\nEle
 vation change - +/-950 feet/290 meters\nDifficulty - 7+/10 - some steep & 
 rocky sections and a seasonal creek crossing. Must be sure footed (confide
 nt and competent)! Bring trekking poles.\nExposure - 99% sun/1% shade - st
 eep\, rocky\, maybe mud\, ticks/insects\, poison oak and cows.\nBring plen
 ty of water! At least 68 oz./2 liters **\\*Think Exposure\\***.\nDogs - Ye
 s\, well behaved fit dogs on a leash are welcome.\nFacilities at trail hea
 d - Picnic tables and restrooms.\nCost - $5 Cash.\nParking - Free but only
  30 parking spaces! Overflow parking on Hwy 1.\n**Get there Early! Carpool
  if you can - This is a very Popular Park!**\nRemember to wear appropriate
  hiking shoes\, bring plenty of water\, for your dog too\, a hat\, snack/l
 unch and layered clothing.\nPlease Do Not Use Any scented products the day
  of a group hike!\nOf course\, we will all look out for each other but ult
 imately\, hikers are responsible for their own safety and well-being durin
 g hikes.\n\n**After Hike Gathering**\nCafé Aquatica\n(One of our favorite
 s\nand dogs are allowed)\n10439 CA-1\, Jenner\, CA 95450\nhttps://www.cafe
 aquaticajenner.com/#/\n\n**When We Meet**\nSaturday April 11\, 2026\n8:30 
 am - 11:30 pm\n**Get there Early! Carpool if you can - This is a very Popu
 lar Park!**\n**If your plans change after you sign up even if you're on th
 e waitlist\, please update your RSVP.**\nDo Not Attend if you are sick\, r
 unning a fever\, were exposed to or have tested positive for Covid-19 or a
 ny other contagion!\nHike may be changed\, rescheduled or cancelled in cas
 e of excessive heat\, rain\, smoke/AQI\, illness\, zombie apocalypse etc..
 . Check your email the night before for any possible changes.\n\n**Notice 
 to New Hikers Only**\n***"When a New Hiker (never hiked with me before) do
 esn't show up (No Show) to their first hike with the group\, they will be 
 removed (not banned) from the group immediately."***
